{"title_page": "Stephen Watson (poet)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Stephen Watson\n| image       = Poet Stephen Watson.jpg\n| image_size  = 199px\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1954|11|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Cape Town, South Africa]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2011|4|10|1954|11|6|df=y}} \n| death_place = [[Cape Town, South Africa]]\n| occupation  = Poet, academic\n| nationality = [[South Africa]]n\n| magnum opus = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n}}\n\n'''Stephen Watson''' (6 November 1954 &ndash; 10 April 2011) was a [[South Africa]]n poet.\n\nMost of his poetry is about the city of [[Cape Town]], where he lived most of his life. He was a professor in English at the [[University of Cape Town]]. He was also the Director of the Writing Centre there, and one of the founders of the Creative Writing Program.\n\nCreatively, he believed that poetry and literature can stand on their own and need not refer to politics, or the struggle for liberation, in order to be valid.<ref>Charlotte Otter, [http://charlotteotter.wordpress.com/2007/11/12/poets-and-politics/ \"Poets and Politics\"] Charlotte's Web, 12 November 2007.</ref> He took a strong stand on poetic relativism, believing it was possible and desirable to differentiate between \"good\" and \"bad\" poetry - a stance that has drawn criticism.<ref>[http://www.chico.mweb.co.za/art/2008/2008jan/080118-shift.html/ Titlestad: Aesthetes and democrats: reading the critical reception of The heart in exile and Sue Clark's The False Bay cycle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080330062457/http://www.chico.mweb.co.za/art/2008/2008jan/080118-shift.html |date=30 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAs a literary critic, Watson suggested that \"South Africa is held together by a nexus of peoples 'dreaming' each other in terms of the myths that the distance between them creates.\"<ref>Watson, S. 1980. ''The Liberal Ideology and Some South African Novelists''. Cape Town: University of Cape Town.</ref>\n\nWatson was anchored at the [[University of Cape Town]] for most of his career. In his poetry, he was best known as a lyrical chronicler of the Cape's natural beauty, documenting the response of the soul when surrounded by it. His intertwinedness with the landscape spilled into his prose, too: he memorably wrote about his \"love affair\" with the city's mountains last year, in what might be cast as a follow-up essay to his landmark 1990 piece, \"In These Mountains\". Although poetry was Watson's chief metier, he distinguished himself as an essayist, writing on subjects near and far, as diverse as South African \"black\" poetry and [[Leonard Cohen]].<ref name=BookLive>[http://book.co.za/blog/2011/04/11/stephen-watson-rip \"Stephen Watson, RIP\"]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Books Live'', 11 April 2011.</ref>\n\nIn February 2006, the normally reclusive Watson made the mainstream news when, writing in ''[[New Contrast]]'', he launched an attack on [[Antjie Krog]], accusing her of plagiarism. He claimed that she \"lifted the entire conception of her book [''the stars say 'tsau' ''] from [his] ''Return of the Moon''\", and that she also plagiarised from the work of [[Ted Hughes]]. Krog strongly denied the claims.<ref>[http://www.mg.co.za/articlePage.aspx?articleid=264818&area=/breaking_news/breaking_news__national/ Antjie Krog denies plagiarism claims] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814151746/http://www.mg.co.za/articlePage.aspx?articleid=264818&area=%2Fbreaking_news%2Fbreaking_news__national%2F |date=14 August 2007 }}</ref><ref>Rory Carroll, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/feb/21/books.southafrica/ \"South African author accused of plagiarism\"], ''The Guardian'', 21 February 2006.</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, Watson received the English Academy's [[Thomas Pringle]] Award for a short story, \"Buiten Street\", published in ''New Contrast''. His poetry featured in the most recent edition of ''Poetry International \u2013 South Africa'', where further biographical information is available.\n\nStephen Watson died on 10 April 2011 after suffering from cancer.<ref name=BookLive />\n\n==Poetry==\n\n* ''Poems 1977-1982''. [[Bateleur Press]] (1982)\n* ''In This City''. David Phillips Publishers (1986)\n* ''Cape Town Days''. (1989)\n* ''Return of the moon: Versions from the /Xam''. Carrefour (1991)\n* ''Song of the Broken String: After the /Xam Bushmen: Poems from a Lost Oral''. Sheep Meadow Press (1991)\n* ''Remembering the Night''. Turret Bookshop (1992)\n* ''Presence of the Earth: New Poems''. David Phillips Publishers (1995)\n* ''The Other City: Selected Poems 1977\u20131999''. David Phillips Publishers (2000)\n* ''The Light Echo And Other Poems''. Penguin Group (SA) (2007)\n\n==Other works==\n\n* ''Stephen Watson: Selected essays, 1980-1990''. Carrefour (1990)\n* ''[[Guy Butler (poet)|Guy Butler]]: Essays and Lectures 1949-1991''. David Phillips Publishers (1994)\n* ''Critical Perspectives on [[J. M. Coetzee]]'' (editor). David Phillips Publishers (1995)\n* ''A City Imagined: Cape Town and the Meanings of a Place'' (editor). Penguin Group (SA) (2006)\n* ''The Music in the Ice'', Penguin Group (SA) (2010)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://mg.co.za/article/2011-04-15-melancholy-and-light/ |title=Melancholy and light |work=Mail & Guardian |accessdate=11 October 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tonight.co.za/index.php?fArticleId=3317857&fSectionId=358&fSetId=251 A City Imagined - Stephen Watson]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080330062457/http://www.chico.mweb.co.za/art/2008/2008jan/080118-shift.html Review of ''The Light Echo and Other Poems'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050912173736/http://users.iafrica.com/h/ho/hornpet/mail-sargasso.html Watson's review of ''The Heart in Exile''] (a collection of South African poetry)\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=2Vb5EEm2a2EC&dq=stephen+watson+the+other+city&sitesec=reviews Review of ''The Other City'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watson, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:South African poets]]\n[[Category:University of Cape Town academics]]\n[[Category:20th-century poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Stephen Watson\n| image       = Poet Stephen Watson.jpg\n| image_size  = 199px\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1954|11|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Cape Town, South Africa]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2011|4|10|1954|11|6|df=y}} \n| death_place = [[Cape Town, South Africa]]\n| occupation  = Poet, academic\n| nationality = [[South Africa]]n\n| magnum opus = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n}}\n\n'''Stephen Watson''' (6 November 1954 &ndash; 10 April 2011) was a [[South Africa]]n poet.\n\nMost of his poetry is about the city of [[Cape Town]], where he lived most of his life. He was a professor in English at the [[University of Cape Town]]. He was also the Director of the Writing Centre there, and one of the founders of the Creative Writing Program.\n\nCreatively, he believed that poetry and literature can stand on their own and need not refer to politics, or the struggle for liberation, in order to be valid.<ref>Charlotte Otter, [http://charlotteotter.wordpress.com/2007/11/12/poets-and-politics/ \"Poets and Politics\"] Charlotte's Web, 12 November 2007.</ref> He took a strong stand on poetic relativism, believing it was possible and desirable to differentiate between \"good\" and \"bad\" poetry - a stance that has drawn criticism.<ref>[http://www.chico.mweb.co.za/art/2008/2008jan/080118-shift.html/ Titlestad: Aesthetes and democrats: reading the critical reception of The heart in exile and Sue Clark's The False Bay cycle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080330062457/http://www.chico.mweb.co.za/art/2008/2008jan/080118-shift.html |date=30 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAs a literary critic, Watson suggested that \"South Africa is held together by a nexus of peoples 'dreaming' each other in terms of the myths that the distance between them creates.\"<ref>Watson, S. 1980. ''The Liberal Ideology and Some South African Novelists''. Cape Town: University of Cape Town.</ref>\n\nWatson was anchored at the [[University of Cape Town]] for most of his career. In his poetry, he was best known as a lyrical chronicler of the Cape\u2019s natural beauty, documenting the response of the soul when surrounded by it. His intertwinedness with the landscape spilled into his prose, too: he memorably wrote about his \"love affair\" with the city\u2019s mountains last year, in what might be cast as a follow-up essay to his landmark 1990 piece, \"In These Mountains\". Although poetry was Watson\u2019s chief metier, he distinguished himself as an essayist, writing on subjects near and far, as diverse as South African \"black\" poetry and [[Leonard Cohen]].<ref name=BookLive>[http://book.co.za/blog/2011/04/11/stephen-watson-rip \"Stephen Watson, RIP\"]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Books Live'', 11 April 2011.</ref>\n\nIn February 2006, the normally reclusive Watson made the mainstream news when, writing in ''[[New Contrast]]'', he launched an attack on [[Antjie Krog]], accusing her of plagiarism. He claimed that she \"lifted the entire conception of her book [''the stars say 'tsau' ''] from [his] ''Return of the Moon''\", and that she also plagiarised from the work of [[Ted Hughes]]. Krog strongly denied the claims.<ref>[http://www.mg.co.za/articlePage.aspx?articleid=264818&area=/breaking_news/breaking_news__national/ Antjie Krog denies plagiarism claims] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814151746/http://www.mg.co.za/articlePage.aspx?articleid=264818&area=%2Fbreaking_news%2Fbreaking_news__national%2F |date=14 August 2007 }}</ref><ref>Rory Carroll, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/feb/21/books.southafrica/ \"South African author accused of plagiarism\"], ''The Guardian'', 21 February 2006.</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, Watson received the English Academy\u2019s [[Thomas Pringle]] Award for a short story, \"Buiten Street\", published in ''New Contrast''. His poetry featured in the most recent edition of ''Poetry International \u2013 South Africa'', where further biographical information is available.\n\nStephen Watson died on 10 April 2011 after suffering from cancer.<ref name=BookLive />\n\n==Poetry==\n\n* ''Poems 1977-1982''. [[Bateleur Press]] (1982)\n* ''In This City''. David Phillips Publishers (1986)\n* ''Cape Town Days''. (1989)\n* ''Return of the moon: Versions from the /Xam''. Carrefour (1991)\n* ''Song of the Broken String: After the /Xam Bushmen: Poems from a Lost Oral''. Sheep Meadow Press (1991)\n* ''Remembering the Night''. Turret Bookshop (1992)\n* ''Presence of the Earth: New Poems''. David Phillips Publishers (1995)\n* ''The Other City: Selected Poems 1977\u20131999''. David Phillips Publishers (2000)\n* ''The Light Echo And Other Poems''. Penguin Group (SA) (2007)\n\n==Other works==\n\n* ''Stephen Watson: Selected essays, 1980-1990''. Carrefour (1990)\n* ''[[Guy Butler (poet)|Guy Butler]]: Essays and Lectures 1949-1991''. David Phillips Publishers (1994)\n* ''Critical Perspectives on [[J. M. Coetzee]]'' (editor). David Phillips Publishers (1995)\n* ''A City Imagined: Cape Town and the Meanings of a Place'' (editor). Penguin Group (SA) (2006)\n* ''The Music in the Ice'', Penguin Group (SA) (2010)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://mg.co.za/article/2011-04-15-melancholy-and-light/ |title=Melancholy and light |work=Mail & Guardian |accessdate=11 October 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tonight.co.za/index.php?fArticleId=3317857&fSectionId=358&fSetId=251 A City Imagined - Stephen Watson]\n* 